\section{Executive Summary}
In January 2018, I produced a detailed report\parencite{morrison2018}, commissioned by Gary Johnston from Submarines for Australia, in order to examine the question of the efficiency of a pumpjet.   Pumpjets, whilst common on nuclear submarines which can operate at high speeds (above 25kt) for sustained periods, are generally not used on diesel-electric submarine, which need to operate at very low speeds (around 10kt during transit, and under 5kt during combat operations).  Considerable emphasis had been placed on the significancw of the pumpjet proposed in successful French bid made by DCNS (now Naval Group) for Australia's Future Submarine.  I concluded that an inevitable characateristic of pumpjets - directly necessitated by the characteristics which gave them good acoustic performance at high speeds - was very low propulsive performance (efficiency) at low speeds.  This would mean that a diesel-electric submarine would suffer poorer range and endurance, and significantly worse dived range and endurance, as well as a worse indiscretion ratio due to the use of pumpjets.  Given the profound importance of these characteristics to all diesel-electric submarines, aswell as elevated importance of range and endurance to the Australian requirement, it would appear that a pumpjet can be safely regarded as entirely unsuitable for Australia's Future Submarine.

On June 7 2018, I appeared as a witness before the Senate Economic References Committee \parencite{SEN2018morrison}, where I defended and expanded upon my results, including in the presence of senior officials from Defence and Naval Group, who steadfastly refused to comment.  The Committee directed Defence to provide a written response to my paper prior to the conclusion of the Inquiry Into the Future Of Naval Shipbuilding Industy in Australia on 27th of June, which they finally produced in mid September.  Submarines for Australia had already commissioned me to write a subsequent report in reply to the responses that had appeared in responses to Questions on Notice in Parliament, and also in the media.  With Defence's submission finally received, this paper is in a position to comprehensively assess the totalality of the arguments put by Defence against the conclusions of my previous paper.

With the receipt of the written report it has become clear that Defence has no credible basis for rejecting the findings of my research, and instead has disgraced their technical credibility with utterly ridiculous misrepresentations of the relevant physics.  Their claim that pumpjets can be efficient across the entire speed range are instead based on the assumption that the resistance faced by fully submerged bodies is ``essentially constant over speed"\parencite{defence2018} \parencite{kerr2018}. This is simply untrue.  It is a bizarre, irrational claim with no basis whatsoever in physics.  It is frankly bewildering that such a claim could be made, given how easily it's falsehood can be established by even moderate research, or simple logic.  If it were true, then submarines and torpedoes would be able to elevate their speed without increased resistance, and consequently reach any speed they might choose without requiring larger motors, or more fuel, and hence attain virtually unlimited range.

The truth is that the resistance of submerged bodies in the real world scales with velocity squared.  This exponential increase in resistance explains why conventional submarines slow to extremely low speeds in order to conserve energy when dived, and has been used by other respected physicists discussing this topic \parencite{davies2017} as well as essentially all scientific literature involved hydrodynamics.  It also explains why a propulsor, which must faces one hundred times as much resistance when travelling at 30kt as it does at 3kt, behaves very differently in these regimes, and consequently has a different efficiency.  For Defence, assisted by DSTG, to claim that the relationshp between drag resistance and speed under-water is constant is an extremely shocking revelation.  In the engineering/technical community, it would be just as strange to hear that a dentist with teenage children believes in the tooth-fairy.  Not only is is their job to know otherwise, but abundant life experience would have continually proven otherwise.

An unavoidable conclusion is that claims made by Defence to Parliament in response to Questions on Notice claiming that the pumpjet can be efficient across the entire speed range are entirely baseless and extremely misleading.

Such a revelation necessitates a further question regarding whether such misleading claims where made out of complete ignorance and incompetence, or whether they were deliberately intended to deceive.  As can be seen from the chronology of public comments which this report details, it is difficult to see how Defence could hold such a naive and embarrassing view after having their attention drawn to the opposing evidence multiple times, and devoted so much resources to understanding the relevant technologies.  In 2012 Senator Johnston challenged RADM Moffit directly as to why research money was even being directed towards pumpjets, given how obviously inappropriate they were for our use, but RADM Moffit insisted they would still do the work required. In 2017 Defence revealed that a 99 page report was commissioned on pumpjets as part of \$214 million in 'de-risking' research, and that over a million dollars had subsequently been spent on pumpjet research specifically.

Notwithstanding the improbability that the incompetence of Defence is so completely pervasive that all of this research failed to yeild even a basic understanding of hydrodynamics, the probability that the necessary degree of ignorance has occurred through arrangement rather than accident can be most firmly established by three simple propositions, which are made obvious through a reading of this report:

\begin{enumerate}
\item  \textbf{The French know the answer.}  As one of only two countries in the world who have designed and produced both pumpjets and propellers, nuclear and conventional submarines, and fitted and operated each type of propulsor on both types of submarines, there can be no doubt whatsoever that Naval Group and the French Government do have well-formed opinion about the performance of pumpjets on diesel-electric submarines.  They would have extensive operational performance data from their in-service SSBNS which use the pumpjet.  They would have extremely detailed modelling, and tank-test results from the pumpjet from the almost-complete Barracuda class, which has an identical hull diameter to the proposed Shortfin Barracuda. The would have extensive operational performance data from their own Rubis Class nuclear submarines, which still use propellers, as well as the results of earlier tests, confirmed to have occurred by Naval Group Officials, where a pumpjet was fitted to a diesel-electric Agosta Class submarine.  That they have adequate performance data from all the necessary reference points to assess the likely performance of the pumpjet on our own is entirely beyond dispute.

\item  \textbf{The French gave the answer to the Australians.} It would naturally be a matter of profound neglect on the part of Australian officials to fail to ascertain the necessary performance data - both acoustic and propulsive efficiency - from the French during a Competitive Evaluation Process.  Any doubt that this occurred, however, can be reliably dismissed on account of public statements made by DCNS during the CEP claiming proudly that ``The stealth and hydrodynamic performances of pump jet propulsion are of course classified and in Australia known only to DCNS and the Australian Government."\parencite{costello2016}. Given RADM Sammut's repeated statements \parencite{SEN2016sammut} \parencite{SEN2017hanson} to Senate Estimates that  ``the way in which technical data would be transferred to Australia and the way in which intellectual property would be managed" was one of the reasons that DCNS was selected as design partner, and DCNS's clear pride in  ``the offer from France to transfer to Australia sovereign control and use of pump-jet propulsion technology" there can also be no doubt that after the conclusion of the CEP and the commencement of design, absolutely nothing would have prevented Australia seeking further performance details or reference points, or even assistance in interpretation in the case that the information provided in the CEP was found to be insufficient.

\item \textbf{The Australians can't produce the answer, and are instead denying one exists.} Instead of countering my report by claiming that they have examined test results provided by the French, (or from their own research and modelling) which demonstrates that pumpjet efficiency does not decline at low speeds as I have concluded, Defence is now disgracing themselves with a series of entirely implausible arguments which amount to arguing that no adequate reference point really exists, and therefore the answer cannot be known.  In simple terms, those arguments are:

\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{The hull and the pumpjet need to be `tuned' to each other.} This is the longest-running argument, which has been made repeatedly by RADM Sammut in sequential years \parencite{sammut2017}, \parencite{bergmann2018}, in answers to Questions on Notice \ref{QON1}, and by Chief of Maritime at DSTG \parencite{kerr2018} as well as the final response to my paper.\parencite{defence2018}.  It constitutes an attempt to deny that other nuclear submarines, including the nuclear Barracuda, serve as an adequate reference point to assess the probable performance of the pumpjet on the Shortfin Barracuda.  It requires an enormous contortion of logic order to argue that the performance of the pumpjet we will have can't be known on account of the hull.  It would be equally fair to argue that one cannot know how a pair of shoes would perform in a given circumstance without simultaneously tuning them to a pair of socks. Whilst it is true that the two have to work in close conjunction with each other and a particularly poor match might impair performance, it is necessary (and sufficient) during concept design to assume that a competent (or even ideal) match is made in order to assess the overall suitability of the system.  The implausibility of this argument is further cemented by just how much emphasis has been given to the fact that the Shortfin Barracuda will have \textit{exactly the same} diameter hull as the nuclear cousin from which it is derived \ref{SEN2017hanson}, \parencite{kerr2017}, which ought to make adjustments to the pumpjet on account of the hull entirely unwarranted.

\item \textbf{The weight of the pumpjet makes it inappropriate for smaller diesel-electric submarines, but not for larger ones.} This argument has only occurred recently, first made by former CEO of Naval Group Australia Brent Clark \parencite{clark2018}, (to which I responded\parencite{morrison2018b}), and then later explained in more detail by Chief of Maritime at DSTG Dr David Kershaw\parencite{kerr2018}.  It is an attempt to deny that any other non-nuclear submarine, including every operating class in existence (none of which pumpjets) constitute an adequate reference point for assessing the likely performance of the pumpjet on our future non-nuclear submarine.  It is demonstrably ridiculous, since if a smaller submarine could not maintain proper balance and buoyancy with a heavy pumpjet attached to its tail, then the the submarine would be doomed to either tail-stand or sink, which would amount to a catastrophic failure if ever such a submarine were to detach from its moorings. That this is not the case is amply demonstrated by the fact that both the French and Russians have succeeded in fitting pumpjets to small submarines, and such catastrophes were avoided.  The Russian test boat, B-871 `Alrosa' still operates regularly in the Black Sea.\footnote{The Black Sea is an inland sea about half the size of NSW, which shares borders only with Romania, Bulgaria, Georgia, Ukraine and Turkey. Russia operates a fleet of seven Kilo Class Submarines in the Black Sea, mostly out of Sevastopol, the port which it aquired control of through the 2014 annexation of Crimea.  The Black Sea might thus be described appropriately as a `Russian Lake', where the endurance and range penalties imposed on Alrosa by the pumpjet might be tolerated.  None of the Kilo Class Submarines produced since Alrosa have a pumpjet, and none of the 15 Russian Kilo Class submarines operating in the Northern, Pacific, or Baltic Fleets have pumpjets.}

\item \textbf{The resistance of submerged bodies is constant with speed, unlike that of ships who encounter wave-making resistance.}  This is the most recent, and the most utterly and demonstrably false claim, made both by Dr David Kershaw of DSTG in an interview with Australian Defence Magazine \parencite{kerr2018}, and in Defence's considered written submission to the Senate Economic References Committee \parencite{defence2018}.  It constitutes a clearly desperate and severely embarrassing attempt to argue the no propulsion system of any sort as tested or demonstrated on a surface vessel serves as any kind of reference point for its performance on a submarine.  It is true that ships have the \textit{additional} resistance from wave-making resistance, but for most displacement vessels operating at design speed (and certainly all submarines) pressure drag and skin friction on the submerged part of the hull tend to dominate, both of which scale with velocity squared.  Consequently, the `advance ratio' (how far forward through the water a propeller moves for a given degree of rotation) changes enormously with speed, for a submarine just as it does for a surface ship, and efficiency consequently changes along with this.

\end{itemize}

\end{enumerate}

As noted by Andrew Davies when he contemplated the possibility that `Naval Group is pulling the wool over the eyes of a clueless Commonwealth' with the pump jet, extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence \parencite{davies2017}.  There can be no doubt that such extraordinary evidence of cluelessness has now been supplied by the Department of Defence themselves. But this evidence, revealing impression of cluelessness so complete, is difficult to reconcile with the adamant insistence of competence and confidence in the choice, given by multiple senior officials in the face of sustained questions backed up by substantial evidence. It is so extraordinary that it demands the question of whether the appointed officials who represent the Commonwealth are indeed `clueless' or whether officials in the Navy and Department of Defence are actually conspiring with Naval Group and the French Government to pull the wool over the eyes of a clueless Parliament, as well as the properly elected members of the executive who ultimately signed off on the purchase, and the Australian public at large.

The gravity of such a conclusion is difficult to understate, given the likely nature of the motives which would attend to such a decision.  One would presume that one would not advance into the public arena a submarine design which was known to be unviable, and lead to deep embarassment and ridicule if subjected to thorough scrutiny, unless the real motive for the design or partner choice was even less capable of withstanding public scrutiny.  The possibility that this is the case must be considered very seriously, given the difficulty of reconciling recent events with the counterfactual proposition:

After the initial publication of my first report, three Questions on Notice were asked by Senator Ketter, specifically referencing my report \ref{QON1}.  Whilst Defence avoiding answering all of them directly, one of them was particularly brazenly side-stepped.  Asked ``Is Defence still confident that Naval Group still hold the opinion that the pump-jet is well suited to diesel-electric submarines?" Defence merely reiterated their intent to use the pumpjets as offered, strictly avoiding mentioning anyone's opinion, either their own or Naval Group's.  If the answer actually was what we would all assume it should be, that should be a very easy answer to directly.  A simple `yes' would do just fine.  If the answer is `no', then we must assume that at the time of writing (presumeably before the return date of 3 April, though Defence isn't always timely) that Defence an inkling (at the very least) of what Naval Group undoubtedly knew all along - that pumpjets are entirely unsuitable for diesel-electric submarines.  In avoiding answering the question directly, Defence was not just misleading the parliament, but clearly acting to shelter Naval Group from subsequent accusations of fraudulent or misleading conduct during the CEP.

Giving Defence the most generous possible interpretation, one might allow the possibility that Defence were just coming to grips with being completely hood-winked during the CEP by their chosen design-partner, and perhaps they felt that their wrath at being deliberately deceived ought not be publicly vented, or at least not at this stage.  One might, at a stretch, allow that maintaining the opportunity for the partner to save-face was still a useful bargaining-chip that our Defence chiefs to use in order to bring a potentially treacherous contractor to heel, along with a range of contractual penalties, as well as the commercial leverage the Commonwealth would have by being able to re-introduce competition into the design process as many have suggested ought be done in any case \parencite{stanford2017}, or not proceed to a build contract on completion of the design.

The state of commercial negotiatons between the Commonwealth and Naval Group, as revealed in the Senate Economic References Committee \parencite{SEN2018morrison}, reveal that Defence was moving on exactly the opposite tack - shocking Senators with the revelation that Defence was actually moving instead to contract immediately with DCNS for the full construction of all 12 submarines, to the complete exclusion of the Australian Submarine Corporation, within coming weeks, effectively wiping out the opportunity for any competitive tension at any stage of the ~\$50 billion project.

In light of these events, I find the most plausible explanation to be the worst:
\begin{itemize}
\item The propulsive performance of pumpjets do indeed decline to very low efficiencies at low speeds, making them entirely unsuitable for a diesel-electric submarine which operates almost entirely at such speeds, broadly in line with the findings of my first report.
\item Some group of individuals, including senior French officials from Naval Group as well as the Australian Government, were aware of this fact at the time of the Competitive Evaluation Process, and remains so today.
\item That group has deliberatly cultivated the impression that pump-jets would confer a substantial technological edge to Australia's Future Submarine, knowing that would not be the case, either by virtue of the pump-jets not ultimately being used, or because if they were they would confer a disadvantage.
\item That impression was necessary in order to defend of a choice which selected a design partner who's proposal was both more expensive, and slower to deliver that their competitors, for which no more defensible reason could be found.
\end{itemize}

It appears that the pumpjet idea was simply a lead-character used to construct the fiction that France's vaunted heritage as a designer of nuclear submarines offers a substantial technical advantage to a non-nuclear submarine.  There is almost no chance that it will be included in the detailed design.  In reality, without a nuclear reactor, there is barely any relevant technology or experience (other than the combat system, mandated from a 3rd party) which is usefully transferrable.  The extent to which the bottom of the barrel needed to be scraped was illustrated when RADM Sammut was challenged on the benefit of the nuclear design, other than pump-jets \ref{SENhanson}, and he was forced to refer to the `diameter of the hull' as being a key learning, a prospect which would be much more easily subjected to public ridicule had it been more substantially promoted.\footnote{Amongst the many engineering challenges presented in designing a new submarine, ensuring the structural integrity of the hull at a new diameter is one of the most well-understood and predictable.  The Collins Class was evolved from a submarine of smaller hull diameter, and this aspect of the design and development encountered no problems.  In 2006, DSTO commissioned a paper suggesting that the Collins Class replacement be designed at a wider hull, which didn't correspond to that of the Barracuda.}  In contrast, those countries whos own navies relied entirely upon diesel-electric submarines would likely boast significant advantages in technologies which are genuine game-changers for diesel-electric submarines, such as advanced composite propellers, Air-Independent Propulsion, and Lithium-Ion batteries, which we are now told won't be included in the Future Submarine \textit{because} of the pumpjet\parencite{bergmann2018}.

Australians have a right to know what the true motive of Defence was in choosing the French as a design partner.  There can be no doubt that the pumpjet played no legitimate part in it.  Any claims to the contrary are made either out of obscene incompetence, as Defence's latest response might have us believe, or more likely are made with the intent of being misleading.


\section{Introduction} \label{intro}

The pumpjet propulsion system is a key feature of Naval Group's Shortfin Barracuda submarine concept, and was apparently a key reason why the concept was selected by the Australian Government as the basis for the design of Australia's new submarine under project SEA 1000.  Naval Group's official website, reinforced by comments from officials representing both Naval Group and the Australian Government,  claims that the pumpjet system offers acoustic advantages which will make the Shortfin Barracuda much more effective than a submarine driven by a conventional propeller.

However, over a number of years now the pumpjet choice has attracted sustained attention and criticism, mostly around its efficiency at low speeds, where a diesel-electric submarine would necessarily spend a great deal of its operating time.  I was commissioned by Gary Johnston of Submarines for Australia to investigate this topic in detail and produce a report \parencite{morrison2018}, which concluded that a very substantial reduction in dived range and endurance (as well as overall range) would necessarily result from the pumpjet choice.  Furthermore, that paper challenged the assumption that the pumpjet would be acoustically superior at low speeds, where open propellers would have no cavitation, and cause much less turbulence than the equivalent jet.

That paper, and a subsequent blog post \parencite{morrison2018a} on the topic which made the paper publically available, attracted the interest of the Senate Economics Reference Committee Inquiry into the Future of Naval Shipbuilding in Australia.  Senator Chris Ketter asked written questions on notice to the Department of Defence requesting responses to the paper specifically, and related comments from public officials, with a return date of 3rd April 2018.  I was also invited to provide evidence to the committee in a public hearing on the 7th of June 2018.  In that public hearing \ref{SENmorrison}, I stood by the conclusion of my substantive paper, which was: ``between two otherwise identical submarines, the one with the pump jet will always have a lower dived endurance, a lower dived range, a worse indiscretion ratio, a lower overall endurance and a lower overall range than the one with the propeller."  In the presence of both the outgoing acting CEO of Naval Group Australia Brent Clark, and General Manager of Submarines (for Defence) Stephen Johnson, I pointed out that that statement was yet to be challenged, and that I'd be very surprised if anyone with technical competence or professional integrity sought to challenge it.

In their own evidence during the course of the day, neither of those two did choose to challenge it.  Senator Kim Carr requested that defence produce a written response to that report for the committee prior to their handing down of their finaly report for the Inquiry, and Defence agreed to do their best in the time available, with the head of Capability and Sustainment Group (CASG) Kim Gillis assuring the committee that ``We  will  provide  the  committee  with  the  best  possible  advice  wecan  in  the  shortest  possible  time  frame  to  meet  your  requirements  so  that  you  can  be  betterinformed, because we do hold that expertise." Senator Carr emphasised the importance of timeliness that ``it would look pretty bloody stupid after the report's handed in''. Despite these exhortations, in the final report of the committee this request, and defence's acceptance of it was noted, but no acknowledgement was made of whether any response was actually received, or what it contained \parencite{SERC2018final}.

In the August edition of Australian Defence Magazine a feature article on the titled `Future Submarine: Pumpjet propulsor technology choice still not well explained' \parencite{kerr2018} appeared, referencing both my testimony in the hearing and the paper.  Comment for the article was sought from CASG, the Royal Australian Navy (RAN) and Naval Group, and none was forthcoming.  However, some substantial comments were provided by Dr David Kershaw, the chief of DSTG's Maritime Division, who was also Science and Technology advisor for a time on SEA 1000, the Future Submarine Project.

This paper has been commissioned by Gary Johnston to provide a summary of the responses that have been received from official sources (in government, and Naval Group) to the earlier major report, and respond to them.  At the time of its original commissioning, two substantive arguments emerge seeking to engage with the technical arguments made in the earlier paper.  The first is that the large size of the submarine now makes the pumpjet viable, where as for smaller submarines the large weight of the pumpjet would make it unviable, and that the pumpjet would be generally well-suited to smaller sumbarines as well were it not for this weight consideration.  The second is that interaction between the pumpjet and the hull obviate the evidence I have produced showing that pumpjet efficiency declines at low speeds, which are claimed to neglect considering such interactions.

In early September, the Department of Defence gave a six-page written response to my paper, a full three months after the initial request. The two substantive arguments already identified were repeated, but the weight of their argument actually came to rest on another assumption.  This assumption was mentioned already by Dr Kershaw in the ADM article, but it was so completely at odds with the most basic physics that I was inclined to dismiss it as perhaps a clumsily worded statement made in an interview compounded by a little journalistic mis-quotation, rather than a substantive argument.   The re-appearance of this argument, which was spelled out and repeated multiple times in a written document that was prepared by Defence over the course of three months, well after any nominal deadline for timeliness had elapsed, dispelled all illusions that the argument was included by accident.  As such, I have also addressed it here as the first of three substantial arguments made against my earlier conclusions regarding pumpjet efficiency, which has quite significantly altered the conclusions of this paper, which seeks to consider all three lines of reasoning in sufficient detail to suitably discuss the circumstances in which such arguments might be made.

This paper commences with a chronologically sequenced history of the most significant comments that have been made by public officials or Naval Group/DCNS with respect to the pumpjet, highlighting the most important implications of each in their context.  These are followed by three sections, addressing in more detail the three substantive arguments against my conclusions.  Some discussion developing the final conclusions follows, followed by appendices which include more substantial extracts or originals sources where appropriate, for reference.


\section{A brief chronology of comment}

The following gives a brief overview of the significant known public comments regarding the pumpjet that have been made by official representatives of either the Commonwealth of Australia, or Naval Group, formally known as DCNS.  Only brief quotations are selected here, with references being made to the full excerpts either in Appendices or References.  Any emphasis in-text has been added.

\subsection{RADM Rowan Moffit, Head of SEA 1000, before the Senate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[width=0.9\textwidth, center, colback=red!5!white,colframe=red!75!black, title= \textbf{28 May 2012 - Senate Estimates}]
\textit{Senator Johnston directly challenges Rear Admiral Justin Moffit (then director of SEA 1000) about the pumpjet proposal.  Full exchange in \ref{SENMoffit}. Emphasis added.}
\\
\\
\textbf{Senator JOHNSTON:} I am told that there are no pump jets on any conventional class submarines in the world.
\\
\textbf{Rear Adm. Moffitt:} That is quite right. It might be a very easy task for us to write it off. I do not know, because I have not done-
\\
\textbf{Senator JOHNSTON:} The French and the Russians have tried. No-one has used them. They are not being used on anything other than nuclear powered submarines-particularly the Americans.
\\
\textbf{Rear Adm. Moffitt:} \textbf{If it does not look like it makes sense, I will rule it out. But I cannot give you the answer to that yet because we have not done the work.}
\\
\textbf{Senator JOHNSTON:} Who had the idea to look at pump jets? Where did that come from? Did it come from capability group saying that we had better had a look at that?
\\
\textbf{Rear Adm. Moffitt:} I do not know the answer to that. I doubt that there is a clear answer.

\end{tcolorbox}

This encounter shows that the viability of pumpjets was challenged some time ago.  It is noteworthy at the time that RADM Moffit makes no attempt to defend the consideration, acknowledging even that it might be easy for them to ``write it off".  It is also noteworthy the tone of confidence that Senator Johnston's challenge has, driving directly for an explanation of who had the original idea, which RADM Moffit was unable or unwilling to answer.


\subsection{Naval Group on ASPI Strategist and own website}

\begin{tcolorbox}[width=0.9\textwidth, center, colback=blue!5!white,colframe=blue!75!black, title= \textbf{10 Feb 2016 - Sean Costello, CEO DCNS Australia}]
\textit{In a blog post\parencite{costello2016} for the ASPI Strategist prior to the announcement in April, Sean Costello describes the significance of the pump jet technology to their bid. Emphasis added.}
\\
\\
``As a complete submarine power, we understand conventional propulsion, which is why we also understand that propulsion is but one part of the submarine puzzle. In designing to the Australian requirement, it should come as no surprise then that \textbf{the conventionally powered Shortfin Barracuda Block 1A is only 5\% lighter than its nuclear cousin.}"
\\
\\
``There's no better example of what I'm talking about than the \textbf{offer from France to transfer to Australia sovereign control and use of pump-jet propulsion technology for the Shortfin Barracuda}-technology resident only in France, the UK and the USA. Technology born from the French SSBN program a generation ago. The stealth and hydrodynamic performances of pump jet propulsion are of course classified and in Australia known only to DCNS and the Australian Government."

\end{tcolorbox}

The significance of the pumpjet in Frances bid was clearly acknowledged well before the public announcement of DCNS's success.  It also provides a clear indication that the size of the submarine already appeared to be quite well-known, and was only intended to be a very minor modification from the nuclear Barracuda.  For such a small variation in displacement, it might be very reasonably expected that the length of the submarine would vary (the easiest modification), but the diameter would not need to.  These comments also display quite clearly that the pumpjet technology in France's possession is recognised as common with technology in the US and the UK.  This rules out the likelihood that some special or unique pumpjet technology, better suited just to diesel-electric submarines, had been pioneered by France alone.  This comment also directly implies that information regarding the performance of the pumpjet had already been given to the Australian  government, \textit{prior} to the conclusion of the Competitive Evaluation Process (CEP).

\begin{tcolorbox}[width=0.9\textwidth, center, colback=blue!5!white,colframe=blue!75!black, title= \textbf{8 Apr 2016 - Sean Costello, CEO DCNS Australia, and Gerard Autret, Chief Naval Architect of the Shortfin Barracuda}]
\textit{In a blog post\parencite{autret2016} for the ASPI Strategist prior to the announcement in April, Sean Costello describes a number of the major features and design approaches for the Shortfin Barracuda, including relating the choice of the pumpjet closely to an accoustic requirement to close with another submarine at higher speed.}
\\
\\
``The challenge for any attack submarine is to maintain a nearly silent acoustic signature at a speed necessary to manoeuvre within weapons range of the target. The nuclear Barracuda is designed to \textbf{reduce radiated noise when operating at a speed sufficient in order to close a threat submarine undetected. Of particular importance is the pump-jet propulsor}, which combines a rotor and stator within a duct to significantly reduce the level of radiated noise through the effects of wake harmonisation and avoidance of cavitation."
\end{tcolorbox}

This comment provides clear context for the importance of the pump-jet.  Consistent with the physics outlined in Reference \parencite{morrison2018} the acoustic advantage is only emphasised by DCNS as being significant at higher speeds.  Whether it is viable for a diesel-electric submarine (as opposed to the nuclear one mentioned here) to maintain such speeds to close with many types of targets is left unclear, or at least unmentioned.  As later discussed in my evidence to the Senate \ref{SENmorrison}, this is consistent with DCNS being well aware with the advantages and disadvantages of the pumpjet, whilst not making verifyably false claims.

\begin{tcolorbox}[width=0.9\textwidth, center, colback=blue!5!white,colframe=blue!75!black, title= \textbf{May 2016 onwards - DCNS/Naval Group Website for Shortfin Barracuda}]
\textit{The official website for the submarine claims the advantages of the pumpjet in specific terms, drawing comparisons with ``obsolete propeller technology" and ``otherwise identical submarines".  Last accessed 4 Sept 2018 \parencite{naval2018}. Emphasis added.}
