\section{Discussion}

Having considered in some detail the nature of the three substantive arguments given in opposition to my findings, it is clear that none actually provide any credible evidence to oppose my conclusions.  However, a clear similarit or parallel between the three can be found.  Each of them respectively actually comprise an argument against an obvious reference point being used to assess the efficiency of the pumpjet.

The argument that resistance is constant for underwater bodies, since they encounter no wave-making resistance, seeks to oppose any use of propulsive data derived from propulsors which might be used on ships, including for highly comparable systems (waterjets), or even directly comparable systems (pumpjets, or decelerating ducted propellers).

The argument that the size of the submarine is a game-changer, attempts to dismiss the possibility that any experience with other diesel-electric submarines constitutes and adequate reference-point.

The argument that the hull and the pumpjet need to be tuned together is clearly an argument that is intended to dismiss the possibility than any other nuclear submarine, including the Barracuda from which the Shortfin Barracuda is derived, serves as an adequate reference point.

It is indeed remarkeable that none of the arguments made actually involve pointing to a better reference point than what I have been able to use from open-source literature, or announce that any results from Naval Group directly contradict the findings of my earlier report.  It is a relatively simple proposition that Naval Group, as one of only two countries in the world to have fitted both pumpjets and propellers to both diesel and nuclear submarines, has in its possession the best data possible to serve as reference-points for our submarine.  Detailed modelling, and tank testing from the pumpjet on the Barracuda would certainly provide the best reference, but experience from the in-service Rubis Class (which use propellers) as well as the in-service SSBNs would doubtless also provide adequate data.

As I have argued, I think that there actually are adquate reference points in open-source literature regarding comparable propulsion systems, designed for comparable purposes, employed in relevant and comparable, in order to gain what is really only a very broad, but clear conlcusion: that propulsive efficiency declines inevitably and dramatically at low speeds.

Taking it as given that the French do have posession of adquate of far more detailed performance data, derived from even closer reference points than what I can glean from public literature, one must ask whether that data actually confirms, or contradicts my findings.  Given public claims from DCNS during the CEP that information regarding both the hydrodynmic and acoustic performance of the pumpjet were in Australian government hands in Australia \parencite{costello2016} there can be little doubt Australian officials have access to such information.  Indeed, it would be an inexcuseable oversight if they didn't obtain that information during the CEP.

This poses a seemingly irreconcileable tension between the desparate, implausible arguments currently being made by Defence, and the possibility that they are being made because Defence genuinely doesn't know better, and genuinely believes them to be true.  It seems far more probable that Defence actually is in posession of clear, conclusive evidence which broadly supports the conclusions of my report, and is now deliberately concealing that evidence, and attempting to excuse why they have not drawn the obvious conclusions that any sensible person normally would from that evidence - that a pumpjet is entirely unsuited to a diesel-electric submarine.



